        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Phila Sep 2 1877<lb/></p>
            <p>My Dear Mr Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>I have had<lb/> these questions propounded<lb/> to me and as I know you can<lb/> answer them so much more<lb/> satisfactorily than I can&#44; I<lb/> venture to trouble you.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping it will not be too<lb/> much of a tax on your time<lb/></p>
            <p>I remain Yours Sincerely<lb/>
            Mr J C Lyons<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>believe but to disapprove them.<lb/></p>
            
            <p>I willingly accord<lb/> all respect to the Faith&#44; see<lb/> its simplicity &#38; can readily<lb/> conceive with what earnest<lb/>ness &#38; fervor it might have<lb/> been embraced before the<lb/> Advent of Christ&#44; but the<lb/> more I read &#38; ponder&#44; the<lb/> more am I filled with<lb/> the beauty &#38; comfort of that<lb/> Faith in which I have<lb/> been born &#38; brought up.  I<lb/> have endeavored to make myself<lb/> acquainted with the Jewish<lb/> theory of the origin of <hi rend="underline">Christianity</hi><lb/> the two Faiths have several<lb/> points of Belief in common.<lb/>  There are so few of either Faith<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>that take the trouble to<lb/> inquire into the doctrines<lb/> of the other&#44; that there is<lb/> much misunderstanding.  You<lb/> see no necessity for a<lb/> Mediator&#58; do you think<lb/> any man is able to bear<lb/> the burden of his sins&#63;  Is<lb/> there not comfort in the<lb/> thought that&#44; one took upon<lb/> Himself that burden &#38; died<lb/> that we <hi rend="underline">repenting</hi> might<lb/> be forgiven  You ask for<lb/> proof of the Divinity of <sic>Chist</sic><lb/> What proof is there that<lb/> He was not the Son of God&#44;<lb/> the savior promised long.<lb/>  Will any who have studied<lb/> the life of Christ say that<lb/> He was an imposter a<lb/> deceiver&#63;  The character<lb/> claimed by Him excludes<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>this supposition by its very<lb/> nature.  It was so remote<lb/> from all the ideas &#38; anti&#45;<lb/>cipations of the times so unfit<lb/> to awaken sympathy&#44; that<lb/> it would have been the<lb/> last dream of an imposter<lb/> A deceiver of the dullest<lb/> vision would have forseen<lb/> the bitter scorn &#38; persecution<lb/> to which the assumption of<lb/> such a character would<lb/> have exposed him&#44; nor could<lb/> he have thrown into his<lb/> personation the air of truth&#44;<lb/> &#38; reality.  The part would have<lb/> been too high for him&#44; he<lb/> would have been continually<lb/> overacting or falling short of<lb/> his part Channing says the<lb/> son of the carpenter could no<lb/> more have conceived &#38; sustained<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>this character under motives<lb/> of imposture&#44; than an infants<lb/> arm could repeat the deeds<lb/> of Hercules or his unwakened<lb/> intellect comprehend a rival<lb/></p>
            
            <p>the matchless works of genius<lb/> Then how do you account for<lb/> His wonderful miracles<lb/> the demonstrations of Divine<lb/> anger at His death.  His resurr<lb/>ection &#38; final <sic>assention</sic>&#63;  Were<lb/> not all the <sic>prophicies</sic> fulfilled<lb/> in Him.  It would seem to me<lb/> had I been an Israelite that<lb/> I would have been proud<lb/> to claim Him.  You probably<lb/> have heard Disraelis answer<lb/> to a remark of the Irishman<lb/> Oconor Half the civilized<lb/> world worships a Jew &#38; the<lb/> other half a Jewess I think<lb/> then are so many <sic>indisfalable</sic><lb/> proofs.  I do not ask you to<lb/></p>
        </body>
